<FIRST>r w PM-TaxMailout Bjt   12-26 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Mailout, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Tax Forms in the Mail Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxpayers receive their annual holiday
greetings from Uncle Sam starting today, as the Internal Revenue
Service mails out more than 107 million tax forms and instruction
packages.
   The forms, which have been waiting at post offices across the
nation for weeks, should be in most taxpayers' hands before Jan. 1.
   The IRS always times the mailing, which costs $26 million for
postage and printing, to come right after the crush of Christmas
mail but soon enough to give taxpayers as much time as possible to
complete their returns before the filing deadline, which falls this
year on April 16.
   For taxpayers still reeling from the sweeping changes wrought by
the 1986 Tax Reform Act, the IRS has reassuring words: the new
forms look very much like last year's forms.
   But to the chagrin of IRS officials, one of the few changes
should not have been made, and it could confuse millions of elderly
Americans.
   The IRS is trying to get the word out to taxpayers eligible for
Medicare that they should ignore the lines on the tax form covering
the supplemental Medicare premium. Congress did away with the
premium along with the catastrophic health program it was designed
to fund.
   But Congress did not vote to repeal the controversial program
until late November, long after the IRS forms had gone to the
printers.
   The IRS hopes to keep confusion to a minimum through a publicity
campaign to get word to the 12 million elderly taxpayers who could
be affected. In addition, IRS officials note that the form
taxpayers would need to compute their Medicare premium tax
liability, Form 8808, does not exist.
   ``We believe that taxpayers will not want to pay taxes that they
don't have to pay,'' said IRS official Arthur Altman.
   But Altman said that if taxpayers still include an amount on the
Medicare premium line, the IRS will refund the money.
   This year's returns are accompanied by a special pitch from new
IRS Commissioner Fred T. Goldberg Jr., who urges taxpayers to
consider filing their returns electronically to cut down on the
time it takes to process their refund checks.
   The IRS is providing a special toll-free telephone number,
1-800-424-1040, for people to call for a list of tax preparers in
their area who can file returns electronically.
   In 1988, two-thirds of all taxpayers qualified for a refund,
with the average refund totaling $875.
   All of the changes in this year's forms are explained in the
accompanying instruction booklets, which also include a list of
other IRS publications that offer further help in preparing taxes.
To request additional tax forms and the tax information
publications, taxpayers can call the IRS at 1-800-424-3676.
   Among the changes featured in this year's forms:
   _The personal exemption, the amount you may exempt from taxation
for yourself, your spouse and each dependent, increases to $2,000
per person, up from $1,950 last year.
   _The standard deduction, claimed by people who do not itemize,
rises to $3,100 for a single person, up from $3,000 last year. The
exemption for a couple increases to $5,200, up from $5,000 last
year.
   _Tax rates remain the same at 15 percent, 28 percent and 33
percent with about four of every five taxpayers paying only the
lowest rate. While the rates stay the same, the tax brackets have
been widened so that more income will be taxed at lower rates in
order to compensate for inflation.
   _For the first time, the IRS will include two name lines,
instead of one, in recognition that more married couples have
different last names.
   The IRS is looking for 111.2 million individual tax returns to
be filed this year with 65 percent expected to opt for the
comprehensive Form 1040, designed for taxpayers who itemize or who
have incomes above $50,000 annually.
   Two shorter forms, Form 1040A and the brief nine-line Form
1040EZ, are available for taxpayers who do not itemize and can meet
other qualifications.
   The IRS form each taxpayer receives is based on the form that
taxpayer used last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891226-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     12-26 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Faces Growing Demand for Imported Wheat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is the world's largest wheat producer
but is not keeping pace with its own consumer demand for more
bread, noodles and dumplings.
   As a result, China has been buying huge amounts of wheat from
other countries, including the United States. An Agriculture
Department analyst says import demand will continue to grow, at
least through the turn of the century.
   ``Even though it is the world's largest producer of wheat,
China's domestic demand exceeds supplies,'' says Frederick W. Crook
of the department's Economic Research Service. ``Wheat output has
risen steadily as farmers have boosted yields because of greater
irrigation and use of improved varieties.''
   Crook, in a report on China's wheat economy, said population
growth and ``consumer preference for wheat products'' such as
noodles, steamed dumplings, bread and pastries have spurred demand.
   As the world's most populous country with 1.1 billion people,
even slight changes in per capita use can translate into large
numbers.
   Crook said per capita wheat consumption rose steadily from 29
kilograms in 1960 to 48 kilos in 1978. Then, as supplies increased
because of import and production gains, the average jumped to 90
kilograms per person in 1987.
   A kilogram is about 2.2 pounds. Ninety kilos would be about 198
pounds, or approximately 3.3 bushels of wheat, allowing 60 pounds
per bushel.
   China has been at peaks and valleys as a customer of U.S. wheat
farmers since the early 1970s. Lately, Beijing has been a large and
consistent buyer of U.S. wheat, rivaling the Soviet Union at times.
   In the 1988-89 wheat marketing year that ran through last May
31, China imported almost 8.1 million metric tons of U.S. wheat and
became the largest foreign customer of American growers. The Soviet
Union, by comparison, imported 4.96 million tons in the same period.
   So far in 1989-90, China has bought about 4.7 million tons
against the Soviet Union's purchases as of Dec. 14 of less than 2
million tons.
   A metric ton, the unit favored in world grain trade, is about
2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. It also is
equal to 1,000 kilograms.
   Both China and the Soviet Union have bought large amounts of
wheat under a U.S. price subsidy arrangement, the Export
Enhancement Program. Under EEP, private exporters can sell to
designated foreign countries at reduced prices and then collect
USDA-owned commodities as ``bonuses'' or subsidies to make up the
price difference.
   From a production standpoint, China has been the world's largest
wheat producer in four of the last five years, according to USDA
statistics.
   China's wheat output this year, for example, is estimated at 91
million tons, compared with 89 million for the Soviet Union and
55.6 million for the United States.
   Other major producers this year include: Canada, 24.4 million
tons; Australia, 12.5 million; Argentina, 10.7 million; India, 53
million; Eastern Europe, 42.3 million; and the European Economic
Community, 79.3 million.
   Crook said that by world standards China has achieved ``fairly
high wheat yields'' and is surpassing those in India, Pakistan and
countries which have large areas of non-irrigated wheat, such as
Canada, Australia, the Soviet Union and the United States.
   On the other hand, Crook said wheat yields are higher in Mexico,
France, Poland and Japan.
   Crook said that Chinese experts predict wheat yields will climb
an average of about 1.65 percent a year and that by the year 2000
there will be some decrease in total wheat area. But they claim
that total output by then will increase to between 100 million and
105 million tons.
   ``China's population will continue to grow in the next decade,
and if per capita income continues to rise, demand for wheat will
also increase,'' Crook said. ``However, prospects for rapid gains
in domestic wheat output are dim because little arable (land) can
be shifted to wheat production, and yields are already high.''
   As a result, he added, the outlook for wheat exports to China
``looks promising in the near future.'' But the rate of growth will
depend mostly on the ability of the rest of China's economy to earn
foreign exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
